  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key components in the android-frameworks-base repository:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java) - This is the base Activity class that defines the public API for Android Activities. It contains the key lifecycle callback methods including onCreate(), onStart(), onResume(), onPause(), onStop(), and onDestroy(). These methods are called by the framework at different stages of an activity's lifecycle as the user interacts with the application.\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java) - This class represents the main thread of an Android application. It drives the lifecycle transitions by receiving lifecycle state changes from the system and calling the appropriate lifecycle methods on activities. ActivityThread executes the lifecycle callbacks and manages the application's main event loop.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java) - This is the server-side representation of an Activity in the window manager service. ActivityRecord tracks the state of an activity on the system side and maintains information about the activity's configuration, visibility, and other runtime properties.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java) - This system service manages activity stacks and tasks. It is responsible for coordinating activity launches, transitions between activities, back stack management, and communicating lifecycle state changes to the ActivityThread through ClientTransaction objects that contain lifecycle items.\n\nTogether, these components create a complete lifecycle management system where the ActivityTaskManagerService makes decisions about activity state transitions, ActivityRecord maintains server-side state, and ActivityThread executes the actual lifecycle callbacks on the Activity instances."
}

